my:Hazard.my:ControlMeasures:
a) Permission must be obtained from the Master; 
b) A Safe Work Permit must be issued; 
c) All crew involved must be briefed and a contingency / rescue plan in place and understood by all; 
d) All crew involved must use suitable / appropriate PPE: overalls, safety shoes, hard hat, gloves, etc.; 
e) The enclosed space must be empty (i.e. ballast, fresh water tank, etc.) prior to entry 
f) The enclosed space must be thoroughly ventilated prior to entry; 
g) Ballast/de-ballasting operations must be suspended when entering a ballast tank. Ensure a 'Do Not Operate' sign is posted on the ballast/de-ballasting control board. 
h) Smoking is not permitted, no smoking signs should be placed around the entrance; 
i) The atmosphere in the space must be tested using Drager tubes and oxygen meter prior to entry; 
j) Crew in the enclosed space must be equipped with a personal oxygen meter(s), which must be tested prior to entry; 
k) Two SCBAs and two EEBDs must be on stand-by at the entrance to the enclosed space; 
l) The Officer in charge should monitor progress at all times; 
m) A crew member should be posted at the entrance whilst persons are inside the enclosed space; 
n) Communication must be established and maintained between persons working in the space and crew at the entrance.

a) All crew involved must use suitable / appropriate PPE: overalls, safety shoes, hard hat, gloves, etc.; 
b) Adequate lighting to be provided. Use intrinsically safe portable lighting, if required; 
c) Any opening in the deck (i.e. manhole, grating, etc.) should be secured with guard rails / ropes and adequately lit.

a) Crew to wear adequate PPE to existing temperatures in the enclosed space; 
b) Use of mechanical fans;
c) Breaks should be taken at regular intervals; 
d) Drink sufficient fluids (water) to avoid dehydration - Consumption of alcohol prohibited, soft drinks and coffee should be avoided; 
e) Where possible, all adjacent machinery should be stopped; 
f) Where possible, heating of adjacent compartments (i.e. fuel tank) should be stopped.

a) Use of suitable and appropriate PPE: overalls, safety shoes, hard hat, gloves, etc.; 
b) Suitable lifting equipment and chocks should be used when opening manholes, etc.; 
c) Consult 'Manual Handling' Risk Assessment.
